<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 93 / Revenue seeks to protect tax staff whose jobs may be
contracted out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Inland Revenue has become the first government department to state that
it is seeking to protect the pay and conditions of staff whose jobs might be
contracted out to the private sector.
Mr Steve Matheson, the Revenue's director of operations, has written to
staff, anxious about the effect on their jobs, to tell them that four
prototype 'market testing' schemes involving secretarial staff have been
stopped.
Under market testing, the first step in the process that leads to
contracting out, services provided in-house are tested against the market.
Staff are encouraged to bid for the contract on the same basis as the
private sector.
The Revenue's decision to reorganise market-testing ensures that staff are
covered by Tupe - Transfer of Undertakings (Protection of Employment) -
regulations. These were designed to protect wages and conditions in company
mergers.
The move follows pressure by the union for tax staff, the Inland Revenue
Staff Federation, which last week announced a large majority for industrial
action against market testing. Mr Clive Brooke, the general secretary of the
IRSF, said the Revenue's decision was a 'victory in a battle but not in the
war'.
Mr Matheson said in a circular to staff: 'We have decided not to go ahead
with the market testing of these four areas. We have to organise the work in
such a way as to be as sure as we can that the Tupe regulations will apply.'
In some circumstances the Tupe regulations can apply to contracting-out and
prevent private companies from cutting the pay or worsening the conditions
of civil servants they take on. That could restrict some parts of the big
market-testing programme announced by the government in November.
Market-testing is this year being extended to 44,000 civil servants and the
value of the work being tested has risen from Pounds 25m in 1992 to Pounds
1.5bn in 1993. Next Monday the government is hosting a conference for
private companies on how to compete for that work.
Until now the government has accepted that the Tupe regulations, inspired by
the European Community, do apply in areas where there is clearly a separate
undertaking being contracted-out, but says they do not apply in more loosely
organised functions such as secretarial work.
Each government department can organise market-testing in the way it sees
fit and the Inland Revenue's positive attitude to Tupe may not be repeated
throughout the civil service.
Market testing of secretarial work in the Inland Revenue will still go ahead
but instead of being organised in four small schemes, which might not have
qualified for Tupe protection, it will be organised throughout the Inland
Revenue South West.
Mr Matheson argues that, when restructured, secretarial services are more
likely to be covered by Tupe. But he also warns that job losses will still
be unavoidable.
</TEXT>
<XX>
