FT  15 JAN 93 / Letter: Shetlands confident of overcoming oil disaster
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr M A P MCARTHUR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, The full impact of the oil spillage on the Shetland islands will not be
known for many months, perhaps years.
The oil industry is very much part of the way of life in Shetland and will
continue to be so for a long time to come. However, in addition to the
measures which have long been in place through Shetland Islands Council to
manage Sullom Voe tanker traffic, there must also be increased national and
international efforts to ensure the safe marine transportation of oil and
the protection of the environment by the introduction of additional maritime
regulations.
We must not underestimate the difficult times that we face, but neither
should we overstate them. Our economy has a solid base and we have an
excellent name for producing quality goods and providing good services. It
is very important to let everyone know that we are not going to allow this
disaster to rule us or affect the quality of any of our products or
services.
The Shetland community is made up of resilient people and we will overcome
any difficulties before us. We ask that our customers continue to have faith
in our ability to supply quality products and services.
M A P McArthur,
chair,
Shetland Chamber of
Commerce,
122 Commercial Street,
Lerwick, Scotland ZE1 0HX
