<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This looks like a night to spend just about anywhere other than in front of
the box. However, it is a different story if you are minded to listen to
Tyndale's Testament (Radio 3, 10.45). William Tyndale eminently deserves to
be resurrected from the dog-eared pages of history text-books. A good
scholar and a most courageous man, Tyndale was responsible for the first
complete translation of the Bible into English and tonight's programme
salutes his profound, if unrecognised, influence on English language and
literature.
If you admire people with a creative flair for handling money, the programme
to watch is Arena: On the Road with Boggs (BBC 2, 9.30). J. S. G. Boggs is
the American artist who draws and colours his own dollar-bills and spends
them as a form of 'performance art' which allows him to be remunerated more
handsomely than are most poverty-stricken performance artists. Collectors of
Boggs's work are set a merry dance as they try to track down Boggs-bills
using the receipts which the artist always asks for and which then, together
with the loose change, become part of the art-work.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
