<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 93 / Technology (Worth Watching): Absorbing the bounce
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
English Architectural Glazing has developed a blast-resistant glazed
cladding system, providing extra protection against bomb attack, writes
Richard Lapper. EAG's glass cladding is designed to bend rather than
fracture with the force of a blast - like a tennis racket hit by a ball.
The system uses frames of a special aluminium alloy. Transoms and mullions
are marginally wider than those used in conventional building design,
helping keep the glass in its frame. But Norman Sheldrake, managing
director, says they are narrower than in other blast-proof cladding systems.
The EAG system differs little in appearance or cost from standard claddings.
EAG: UK, 0638 510000.
