<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 93 / DTI report proves painful reading for Bank
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BLUE ARROW affair had a happy ending for National Westminster Bank
yesterday with the publication of a 356-page Department of Trade and
Industry report clearing the bank of allegations that it had behaved
dishonestly.
However, the final chapter in the affair, which has involved two criminal
trials and two DTI reports, is less pleasant for the Bank of England.
The report clears the Bank of allegations that it colluded with NatWest to
prevent the first DTI investigation in 1989.
The three inspectors, Mr Michael Crystal, Mr David Spence and Mr Victor
Temple, are also careful not to make any direct criticism of the Bank.
But their report gives a rare glimpse of the workings of the Bank's
supervisory department, which is responsible for ensuring that banks are
sound and honest.
The picture will not be wholly welcome to the Bank, since it shows the
supervisors as not very aggressive in investigating alleged wrongdoing at a
leading bank, reinforcing the widespread criticisms of the Bank's
supervision of the corrupt Bank of Credit and Commerce International.
In addition, quotations from Bank officials give weight to a second widely
held concern about its role as a supervisor - that officials are somewhat
removed from the real world.
The inspectors asked Mr Robin Leigh-Pemberton, the governor, about his
feelings in February 1988 on learning that the DTI was considering an
investigation into NatWest's role in the Pounds 837m Blue Arrow rights
issue, which had taken place the previous autumn.
Mr Leigh-Pemberton said: 'I rather hoped we might avoid it, with all due
respect to you, because I was very concerned about this in that here we had
the National Westminster Bank, at the pinnacle of the financial
establishment, possibly in difficulties, and I would have liked the matter
to have been cleared up as quickly as possible. I knew from past experience
that some of these inspections can take a long time.'
An unusual insight into banking supervisory policy is also given by Mr Brian
Quinn, the Bank director in charge of supervision.
He said: 'We have - and I think I must say this - a preference for avoiding
official investigations into banks. Banks are essentially about confidence,
and the mere knowledge that there might be an investigation conducted on an
official basis into a bank can have an effect on confidence that we think is
damaging.'
As a result, the Bank encouraged NatWest to carry out an internal
investigation into its role in the Blue Arrow issue. The DTI delayed
launching its own inquiry until the conclusion of this internal probe,
carried out by Sir Philip Wilkinson, NatWest's deputy chairman.
The most interesting part of the report relates to the Bank's involvement in
events leading to the resignations from the NatWest board of three senior
directors - Mr Charles Green, Mr Terry Green and Mr John Plastow - together
with the resignation of Sir Philip from the Bank's Board of Banking
Supervision, which oversees Mr Quinn's supervision department.
Sir Philip's internal report was viewed in both the 1989 DTI report and the
latest one as far too kind to NatWest.
He is criticised for failing to take sufficient legal advice on NatWest's
actions and for failing to pass on to the DTI the serious concerns of
NatWest's inspectors, who had carried out much of the internal investigation
on his behalf.
The Bank was disappointed with Sir Philip and considered declaring that he
was 'not fit and proper for his position as director and chairman of NWIB
(the holding company of NatWest's investment banking activities)'.
That quotation is from a draft letter of July 1989 which was to give notice
to NWIB that its activities were to be restricted under Section 12 of the
1987 Banking Act. But it was never sent.
The inspectors' report shows how Lord Boardman, then NatWest's chairman,
conducted a successful rearguard action to prevent the Bank forcing Sir
Philip's resignation from NatWest. The report says the Bank had the legal
right to demand Sir Philip's resignation from his NatWest posts.
Although Mr Charles Green, Mr Terry Green and Mr Plastow did resign their
posts in July 1989 after criticism of them in the original DTI inspectors'
report, Lord Boardman succeeded in getting the Bank's assurance that it
would not force them to resign - their departure was a matter for NatWest's
board.
There is a fascinating passage in the latest report showing the immense
political pressure upon the governor. In a note written in July 1989, he
writes of the 'chancellor's desire for blood (at NatWest)'.
Mr Leigh-Pemberton explained this note to the inspectors: 'I took the view
that (the chancellor, Mr Nigel Lawson) expected us to require the
resignation of senior people or persons, both from the board of (NatWest) or
(County, its investment bank) and also from the Board of Banking
Supervision.
'At some stage he had said to me he thought it unsuitable in the
circumstances for Sir Philip Wilkinson to go on as a member of the Board of
Banking Supervision.'
</TEXT>
