<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 93 / AEEU recruiting at Nissan suppliers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE AEEU engineering and electrical union has launched a campaign to recruit
members among suppliers to Nissan in north-east England.
The AEEU is the only recognised union at Nissan's Sunderland car plant and
its growth in membership there - to about 2,000 out of 4,600 employees has
helped to maintain its Tyneside numbers against a declining national trend.
The union hopes that by recruiting members at Nissan suppliers it will
strengthen its request for recognition by managements, many of which
rebuffed formal AEEU approaches when they first moved into the area and have
no recognised union on site.
'We have the key - Nissan. We're looking for a knock-on effect,' Mr Davey
Hall, AEEU Tyne district secretary, said. 'It's a continuous campaign. We'll
be on the doorsteps on a number of occasions during 1993.'
AEEU full-time officials are handing out recruitment literature outside
suppliers' premises in the early morning and evening. Mr Hall described the
response from employees as 'tremendous' but admitted that take-up had been
limited. On two occasions AEEU officials have been asked to leave company
car parks.
At Nissan's Sunderland plant the works council, not the union, negotiates
pay and conditions, although some elected representatives are AEEU members.
The plant's 195 European suppliers include 27 in north-east England. The
AEEU is focusing on the 21 that have set up since Nissan arrived in the mid
80s.
One crucial AEEU target - TRW, which supplies Nissan with valves, switches
and machined forgings - said the subject was 'very sensitive'.
Mr Nigel Clark, human resources manager of Reydel, which employs 160 people
at its plant in Washington, Tyne and Wear, making door finishers and centre
console assemblies for Nissan, said, 'We aren't anti-union but we're quite
happy with our current arrangements.'
</TEXT>
