<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Brooke determined to act on press
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE almost insuperable political difficulties for any government in taking a
firm stance on press regulation were tacitly underlined yesterday by Mr
Peter Brooke's Commons statement on Sir David Calcutt QC's report.
The national heritage secretary's gratitude for the review of what he
described as an 'exceptionally difficult and controversial subject' may have
been heartfelt. But, while legal steps safeguarding personal privacy will be
taken, his claim that the review has 'significantly' moved forward the
public debate on press self-regulation is less credible.
The Calcutt report proposed not self-regulation, but statutory controls
enshrined in law. By rejecting that, the government is back at the drawing
board.
Mr Brooke's statement signalled that the government will act on the report's
proposals for new criminal legislation to cope with trespass, electronic
bugging and photographic invasions of privacy. He agreed to take up, among
other things, a proposal to examine a civil remedy - the law of tort - to
protect victims of undue intrusion.
The government risks opening a legal Pandora's box by examining how the Data
Protection Act might contain provisions relevant to the debate - a move that
raises the question of the public's right to scrutinise newspaper files.
Mitigating provisions to protect legitimate press scrutiny on the grounds of
public interest or informing the public about an individual's discharge of
his public functions were also accepted.
In his statement, Mr Brooke broadly endorsed Sir David's caustic views of
the Press Complaints Commission. Commending the report's conclusions as
'compelling', he said that the PCC was not an 'effective regulator' or truly
independent.
On Sir David's central proposal - the creation of a tribunal with legal
powers to punish breaches of a code of conduct - Mr Brooke was unable to
agree.
Citing the constitutional significance of such a change and arguing that it
would depart from the country's traditional approach to press regulation, he
declared: 'The government would be extremely reluctant to pursue that
route.'
Instead, the government has promised to outline its conclusions more fully
on January 29 when Mr Clive Soley, the Labour MP for Hammersmith, presents
his bill to create a right-of-reply law. Final decisions will also await the
findings of the Commons national heritage committee and views of the press
on the Calcutt report.
Responding to questions, Mr Brooke indicated sympathy for suggestions that
the PCC should be strengthened by the introduction of independent members
and for additional powers to impose fines on publications that breached the
standards it laid down.
There was support from some Conservative backbenchers for a suggestion by Mr
Joe Ashton (Lab Bassetlaw) that those who suffered at the hands of the press
should be able to resort to a legal body with a similar status to industrial
tribunals.
Mr Brooke said a central consideration for the government must be how the
private individual could receive efficient and financial redress. Officials
added later that the question of the availability of legal aid was one of
the central issues to be resolved when the question of creating a civil tort
on privacy is examined.
</TEXT>
