<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Cry of 'censorship' against
proposed spike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR Frank Rogers, chairman of the Newspaper Publishers' Association, which
represents national newspapers, said a number of leading publishers would
not oppose action being taken against telephone tapping and other forms of
physical intrusion, Raymond Snoddy writes.
But Sir Frank, who is deputy chairman of The Daily Telegraph, warned: 'The
government would be extremely unwise to frame an act of parliament
specifically directed against journalists.'
Mr Andrew Neil, editor of The Sunday Times, said: 'If the government were to
implement all of this it would be the most draconian censorship rules faced
in peacetime ever.' He said the measures would 'enormously increase
injunctive power', but did not oppose the law being brought up to date on
electronic surveillance, as long as there was a public-interest defence.
Mr Peter Preston, editor of The Guardian and a member of the Press
Complaints Commission, accused Sir David of having a closed mind and being
'a terribly biased witness' because proposals he made after his 1990 inquiry
had not been implemented.
The Newspaper Society, which represents regional and local newspapers, said
the government should have rejected outright Sir David's 'authoritarian
measures'. Mr Dugal Nisbet-Smith, director of the Newspaper Society, said:
'Freedom of expression in Britain remains under threat.'
Earlier in the day, before publication of the Calcutt report, Mr Andreas
Whittam Smith, editor of The Independent, told the national heritage
committee that the media had 'unduly and wrongly' invaded people's privacy.
He backed new laws against trespass, electronic eavesdropping and 'peeping
Tom pictures'.
