<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Reforms would curb 'wildest
excesses'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR David Calcutt QC recommended yesterday that a wide range of measures
should be taken against the press to protect individual privacy, including
the setting up of a statutory tribunal with the power to restrain
publication and to fine newspapers up to 1 per cent of annual revenue.
In his much-leaked report, Review of Self-Regulation, published yesterday
after a six-month study, Sir David concluded that press self-regulation
under the Press Complaints Commission had not worked.
He called for the creation of new criminal offences against physical
intrusion, such as using surveillance devices, with fines of up to Pounds
5,000.
He also recommended that the government consider introducing a new tort
(civil wrong) of infringement of privacy. It could not be restricted to the
press - it would have to include all the media and cover a wide range of
human and technological activities.
Sir David, Master of Magdalene College, Cambridge, also called on the
government to consider:
Whether the Data Protection Act's provisions are relevant for tackling
misrepresentation of intrusion into personal privacy by the press.
Whether further legislation on interception of telephone calls is needed.
Whether legislation preventing the identification of minors involved in
court cases should be amended to remove inconsistencies.
Sir David said his recommendations were designed to make a positive
contribution to the development of the highest standards of journalism 'to
enable the press to operate freely and responsibly and to give it the
backing needed in a fiercely competitive market, to resist the wildest
excesses'.
They were not designed to suppress free speech or stultify a vibrant and
dynamic press.
'They are designed principally to ensure that privacy, which all agree
should be respected, is protected from unjustifiable intrusion, and
protected by a body in which the public, as well as the press, has
confidence.'
Many of the proposals closely follow the regime Sir David recommended in
1990 should be imposed if 'the last chance' for self-regulation were to
fail.
That was when his committee published its report on 'privacy and related
matters'. His verdict on the performance of Lord McGregor's PCC  - which
replaced the Press Council under the Calcutt Committee recommendations - is
unambiguous. He said the PCC had not turned out to be an effective regulator
of the press - it was largely a creature of the newspaper industry, its
members had not been independently appointed, the code of practice had been
watered down, and no 'hotline' had been set up for those who feared their
privacy was about to be invaded.
'The commission has not been set up in a way, and is not operating a code of
practice, which enables it to command not only press but also public
confidence,' Sir David said. He said the PCC was not holding the balance
fairly between the press and the individual.
He was also concerned about the PCC's handling of the serialisation of Mr
Andrew Morton's book on Princess Diana and of reporting of stories
concerning Mr David Mellor, the former National Heritage secretary, and the
actress Ms Antonia de Sancha 'and the commission's apparent lack of public
action in other cases involving public figures where some action might
reasonably have been expected'.
Sir David said that nothing he had learned about the press led him to
believe it would make the changes needed, and the answer was a statutory
tribunal chaired by a judge or senior lawyer.
The report does not give extensive evidence, other than criticism of the way
the PCC was set up, to justify the view that self-regulation had failed and
could never be made to work.
'The review received evidence from several private individuals who were
unhappy with the way they had been treated by the press,' Sir David said.
Claims included inaccurate reporting, harassment, the taking and publication
of unauthorised photographs and the invasion of privacy of hospital patients
or grieving relatives.
Sir David's main remedy, a statutory press complaints tribunal, could not
only 'restrain publication of material in breach of the code of practice' by
means of injunctions and impose fines.
The new offences of physical intrusion - entering private property without
consent, using surveillance devices without consent, and taking photographs
or recordings without consent on private property - would be summary
offences not carrying a prison sentence.
Sir David proposed that the High Court be able to grant injunctions
preventing publication of material obtained by any of the proposed offences.
</TEXT>
<XX>
