<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 93 / Families in need increase by 50%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NUMBER of families receiving income support rose from 2.9m in 1979 to
4.1m in 1989 according to statistics published by the Commons social
security committee yesterday, Alan Pike writes.
By 1989, 6.98m people were living in households dependent on income support,
compared with 4.57m in 1979. The main groups accounting for the growth were
single parents, the unemployed and long-term sick and disabled people. Over
the same period there was a rise of almost 50 per cent in the number of
families with incomes below benefit level - up from 2.05m to 2.97m.
Mr Donald Dewar, shadow social security secretary, said the report
demonstrated that during the 1980s the incomes of those on state benefits
had grown at only half the rate of the population as a whole. He said the
prime minister, 'the self-declared prophet of the classless society', should
read the report with shame.
Social Security Committee. Low Income Statistics: Low Income Families
1979-1989. HMSO. Pounds 10.
</TEXT>
