<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 93 / Review of council grants set to begin
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A THOROUGH review of the way in which the government allocates grant to
councils is likely to begin next month with the aim of introducing changes
in the spring of next year.
The commitment to looking again at the calculation of standard spending
assessments will be critical to ministers in winning the Commons debate due
shortly on the local spending settlement for 1993-94.
Both Tory and opposition MPs have repeatedly criticised the SSA system
through which the government decides how much it thinks councils should
spend - and which thus determines how much grant they receive.
Introducing changes to the SSA methodology for 1994-95 would mean that they
coincide with the use of full information from the 1991 census.
Only raw population data from 1991 have been used in determining grant for
the coming year.
Ministers admit privately that, as the system of limiting or 'capping' local
spending becomes increasingly dependent on SSAs, the present system might
not be 'robust' enough to be a fair basis. But they did not want to
complicate the first year of the new council tax, which replaces the poll
tax in April, with a review of another aspect of local-government finance.
Instead, the 90 local authority delegations which have made representations
to environment ministers about SSAs have been told that the only likely area
for change in the coming year is in the account taken of the removal from
councils of responsibility for further education.
The review of SSAs will cover matters such as whether to change the way in
which the grant reflects the number of people from ethnic minorities in a
particular area, and whether the local unemployment level should become a
factor.
In advance of the Commons debate, Labour yesterday renewed its long-standing
attack on the SSA system with a claim that the calculations were 'partisan'.
Mr Jack Straw, the shadow environment secretary, highlighted government
figures showing that in England Labour councils received an average increase
of 2.5 per cent in their SSAs, while Conservative councils received an
average rise of 3.3 per cent.
</TEXT>
<XX>
