<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 93 / US retail spending surges in December
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US RETAIL sales rose 1.2 per cent between November and December, confirming
anecdotal reports of a surge in consumer spending at the end of last year,
the Commerce Department reported yesterday. They rose 5.1 per cent during
1992 as a whole, making last year the best for retailers since 1989. The
figures are not adjusted for inflation.
The year-end spurt, however, masked significant differences in the fortunes
of particular sectors. Car sales rose 3.2 per cent but general department
store sales fell 0.7 per cent relative to November. Excluding car
dealerships, retail sales rose by only 0.6 per cent.
Separately, the department reported producer prices up by 0.2 per cent last
month and by only 1.9 per cent in 1992 as a whole - the lowest rate of
wholesale inflation since 1983.
Weekly figures for state unemployment claims jumped 52,000 to 343,000, their
largest increase in five months. However, weekly numbers are volatile and
the new total is consistent with sluggish imp-rovement in labour markets.
Economists at C J Lawrence, the New York broker, said yesterday's sales
figures reflected a real increase in consumer spending at an annual rate of
about 4.5 per cent in the fourth quarter, compared with 3.7 per cent in the
third quarter.
Most analysts, however, forecast a slower pace of consumer spending in the
first half of this year. Spending last year ran well ahead of income and
employment growth, resulting in a fall in the already low personal savings
rate.
President-elect Bill Clinton's advisers have refused to rule out a short-run
economic stimulus in part because of worries about the sustainability of a
consumption-led upturn.
</TEXT>
