<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 93 / Fresh tax rules for foreign companies win wary backing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL tax lawyers and foreign governments have responded with
cautious approval to new rules from the US Internal Revenue Service on the
taxation of earnings by foreign-owned companies.
The new rules, put out on a temporary basis, are expected to be less helpful
to foreign corporations than the current ones, which date from the 1960s,
but still represent a significant retreat from proposals put out by the IRS
last year, and widely denounced by US and foreign multinationals as
unworkable.
The Section 482 transfer pricing regulations control the way companies price
the goods and services they exchange with their overseas subsidiaries. Many
members of congress, as well as President-elect Bill Clinton, have claimed
foreign companies manipulate these intra-company prices to make profits
appear at home, rather than at the level of the US subsidiary.
Most international treaties stipulate these transfer prices should be
determined on an arm's-length basis, as if the parent and the subsidiary
were selling their goods or services to an unrelated company. Regulations
proposed by the IRS last year imposed a 'comparable profits interval' test
as a mandatory check that the foreign-owned subsidiary was reporting similar
profits to its US competitors.
Companies will now be able to choose from a variety of approaches, though
required to produce a considerable volume of documentation to justify their
transfer pricing structure. 'They do represent a more realistic approach to
the tests which one must make,' Mr Carr Ferguson, tax partner with the law
firm of Davis, Polk and Wardwell, said.
'It's a lot more acceptable than the proposed regulations, and much more in
keeping with the arm's-length principle,' a European diplomat. added. 'We
think these regulations are fully consistent with the arm's-length
principle,' said Mr Alan Wilensky, assistant-secretary for tax policy at the
US Treasury.
Some accountants warned the new Section 482 rules would impose a burden on
companies to document from the outset the business decisions behind their
transfer pricing structures, rather than attempting to justify their pricing
retrospectively.
It is unclear what future awaits the new rules, promulgated just a week
before the new Clinton administration takes office, but which do not take
effect until April. 'The incoming administration has been given a 90-day
window to act,' said Mr Steven Hannes, national director of transfer pricing
with the accounting firm of Deloitte and Touche.
But Mr Clinton may be under such pressure to fulfil his campaign promise to
levy an extra Dollars 11bn (Pounds 7.2bn) a year from foreign companies that
further legislation is likely, and some Washington lawyers believe foreign
governments need to take tough pre-emptive action. 'Clinton made it an
article of faith. The only thing Congress will listen to is pressure from
the grassroots, and retaliation,' Mr Dan Burt, of the law firm of Burt,
Maner and Miller, said.
</TEXT>
<XX>
