<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 93 / DTI clears NatWest of misconduct
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NATIONAL Westminster Bank, the UK's second biggest bank, was yesterday
cleared by a Department of Trade and Industry investigation of allegations
that it withheld important documents from a 1989 DTI inquiry into the Blue
Arrow affair.
The DTI report said there was 'no substance' to other 'allegations of
dishonesty and impropriety which have been levelled at senior officers of
NatWest'.
The report is less pleasant for the Bank of England, showing its supervisors
as being not very aggressive in probing alleged wrongdoing at a leading
bank.
Lord Alexander, NatWest's chairman, said it was a welcome end to an episode
from which his bank had learned important lessons. He had asked for the
investigation to clear NatWest's name, after criticism of it during the 1991
Blue Arrow trial.
Mr Tom Frost, NatWest deputy chairman who had been accused of misleading the
1989 inquiry, said: 'I am glad that the record has finally been put
straight.'
Also cleared of misconduct was Wilde Sapte, the firm of solicitors which
advised NatWest during the original DTI inquiry.
