<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 93 / Government pledges to outlaw bugging
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY and RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government yesterday pledged immediate steps to make electronic bugging
and trespass criminal offences and promised serious consideration of a civil
remedy against undue intrusion into privacy.
But it stopped short of backing the central plank of Sir David Calcutt's
report into press regulation, that the widely criticised Press Complaints
Commission should be replaced by powerful statutory tribunal.
Mr Peter Brooke, the heritage secretary, endorsed as 'compelling' the
report's findings that the self-regulatory PCC was neither effective nor
independent.
After cabinet discussions of the report yesterday, however, Mr Brooke told
the House of Commons that a statutory body would have a constitutional
significance that departed from Britain's traditional approach to press
regulation.
'In the light of these considerations, the government would be extremely
reluctant to pursue that route,' he said. The report came as two UK
newspapers, the Daily Sport and Kent Today, published the transcript of an
intimate telephone call alleged to be between Prince Charles and Mrs Camilla
Parker-Bowles. The transcript had been published in an Australian magazine
and in some Irish newspapers yesterday. The report recommended a statutory
tribunal able to fine newspapers up to 1 per cent of net annual revenue.
Such a tribunal would also be able to use injunctions to restrain newspapers
from breaching a statutory code.
It is clear the government now plans to take up the suggestion made by Sir
David in his 1990 report that criminal offences be created to prevent
intrusion, for the purpose of publication, using electronic listening
devices and long-lens cameras.
Sir David suggested fines of up to Pounds 5,000 but not prison sentences for
those found guilty. The government is also prepared to give serious
consideration to creating a tort of invasion of privacy, allowing aggrieved
parties to seek redress through civil action, and to look again at existing
legislation on data protection and interception of telephone calls.
Sir David attacked the PCC partly because it had not been set up in the way
he had outlined in his original report and because he thought it had not
done enough in celebrated cases, such as those involving the Royals.
The PCC has decided, for instance, that although there had been complaints
about the printing of topless photographs of the Duchess of York it would
not take them further as the complaints had come from third-parties not
directly involved in the story.
Sir David said his proposals, which drew wide criticism from the newspaper
industry, would enable the press to operate freely and responsibly by giving
it the backing it needed 'in a fiercely competitive market to resist the
wildest excesses'.
Downing Street said the government would draw up its plans for reform after
examining the Commons' heritage select committee's report, due next month,
and hearing newspapers' criticisms of the Calcutt report. Officials said new
legislation was unlikely to be tabled within the current parliamentary
session ending in October.
A clearer view of the government's intentions should come on January 29
during the second reading of Labour MP Clive Soley's private member's bill
to create a statutory right of reply.
Brooke determined to act on press, Page 7
Joe Rogaly, Page 12
Editorial Comment, Page 13
</TEXT>
