<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 93 / Power companies near coal accord
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
REGIONAL electricity chiefs say they are close to successfully concluding
with generators the heads-of-agreement negotiations that will underpin
long-term contracts to buy British coal.
Some believe they can complete the talks by the end of next week, although
they say nothing is likely to be signed before the government publishes its
white paper on energy, probably next month.
Rumours about the progress of the talks helped to raise the price of most
electricity shares yesterday, particularly National Power and PowerGen, the
generators.
The heads-of-agreement talks are being held between 11 of the 12 regional
electricity companies (Recs) of England and Wales and each of the two
generators.
They will provide the basis for the bilateral agreements between regional
companies and generators by which the Recs will buy electricity generated
from British coal.
Although the heads of agreement are fairly detailed, covering such issues as
risk-sharing in the event of unforeseen circumstances, they would leave
individual companies to negotiate price and volumes.
Tariffs for electricity supply, based on the contract prices, are due to be
in place from the beginning of April and the companies would aim to publish
them a month earlier.
The talks assume that deals will last five years in spite of suggestions by
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, that a one-year deal
might be preferable.
Mr Duncan Ross, chairman of Southern Electric, said the heads-of-agreement
talks would help to clear the air for bilateral talks. The regional
companies would want any deals cleared by Offer, the regulator, before
signing them.
National Power said progress had been made in the talks but it was too early
to say when they could be concluded.
Evidence from 327 individuals and organisations had been received at the end
of last week by the Department of Trade and Industry as part of its coal
review, Mr Tim Eggar, energy minister said yesterday.
Editorial Comment, Page 19
</TEXT>
