<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 93 / Ministers to seek early coal industry sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is to push for early privatisation of the coal industry in
spite of the furore over the pit closure programme. Ministers intend to
start work on firm proposals as soon as they put in place the package for
saving some of the 31 pits earmarked for closure last October.
They have concluded that putting British Coal into the private sector is the
best way of ensuring that subsidies to the industry, now seen as an
inevitable part of the package, are ended by the late 1990s.
Legislation on privatisation is likely for the parliamentary session
beginning in the autumn of this year, or the following session at the
latest. Previously, ministers had suggested that the crisis over pit
closures could force a more significant postponement of privatisation, at
least until it could be made commercially viable.
They now believe there is no reason why British Coal should not be
privatised while it still receives subsidies, provided there is a clear
schedule to phase them out.
Ministers are likely to justify the policy stance as putting pressure on
British Coal to improve its performance, and emphasising that the long-term
objective of moving the company into the private sector remains unchanged.
The subsidies, to be collected either from the taxpayer, or, more likely,
through levies on electricity bills, would be aimed largely at enabling
British Coal to replace some of the 20m tonnes of coal imports which come
into the UK each year.
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, will be in Brussels
today to brief European Commission officials on his plans, and ensure that
proposed subsidies for British Coal fit in with EC policies on competition
and on aid to industry.
While still considering a range of ideas to increase British Coal sales to
electricity generators from the proposed level of 40m tonnes in 1993-94 and
30m tonnes in the following four years, the government is moving away from
the idea of closing Magnox nuclear stations which are nearing the end of
their lives. It believes such a move would be too expensive, partly because
of the decommissioning costs, and because relatively few pits or jobs would
be saved, especially as nuclear jobs would then be cut.
Ministers are also unenthusiastic about setting up an energy commission to
supervise the electricity and gas industries, and want to keep the existing
system of regulators for each industry.
But they think that the government might be able to play a larger role in
shaping the industry by supplying information or setting priorities, such as
encouraging renewable forms of energy.
Heseltine clash, Page 6
Editorial Comment, Page 19
</TEXT>
