<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 93 / Insurers wary of new retail regulator
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE INSURANCE industry's support for the Personal Investments Authority, the
proposed regulator of retail financial businesses, has been undermined by a
call for it to set out tougher rules for members, the Association of British
Insurers said yesterday.
Mr Andrew Large, chairman of the Securities and Investments Board, has told
the authority's Formation Committee that it must prove it will bring about a
radical improvement in regulation. The PIA is intended to be formed by the
merger of two self-regulatory organisations - Lautro for unit trust and life
companies, and Fimbra for financial intermediaries. It is intended to be the
lead regulator for firms selling life, pensions and unit trust products.
Mr Large has insisted the PIA's proposed 30-member board be cut to 15, with
a majority of 'public interest' representatives, including consumer
representatives and individuals from outside the financial industry.
He has also said that regulated businesses must be prepared to pay higher
fees to cover tougher regulation and that sales agents and independent
advisers would have to show fitness, properness and adequacy of capital
resources before being allowed to join.
The insurers' association, whose support is crucial to the PIA's success, is
objecting to the suggestion that the board be dominated by public-interest
directors.
Mr Mike Jones, its chief executive, said: 'This looks like a big step down
the road away from practitioner-based self-regulation and not what was
intended under the Financial Services Act.'
Mr Large's letter is said to have been privately welcomed by the banking
industry. The banks' financial services businesses are regulated directly by
the Securities and Investments Board and they have expressed no interest in
switching to the PIA.
One banker said the SIB's conditions for the new body might 'lead to fewer
claims on the investors compensation scheme'. The letter also indicates that
the banks will be regulated under rules formulated by the PIA, a move
calculated to encourage them to join the PIA.
The SIB said yesterday it proposed to charge members of Imro, the
self-regulatory body for the fund management industry, an additional Pounds
350,000 for the 1992-93 fiscal year to cover increased expenditure after the
Maxwell affair.
The estimated fees from members in 1992-93 is Pounds 17.92m, up from Pounds
17.79m in 1991-92.
Editorial Comment, Page 19
</TEXT>
