<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 93 / London Stock Exchange: Gencos up on coal deal hope
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE, JOEL KIBAZO and PETER JOHN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES IN the two main power generators surged as rumours returned that the
new contract to supply the regional electricity companies had been signed.
The deal is due to be tied up by April but the present government
predicament over the fate of the UK mining industry has added spice to the
terms of the contract, and how it will affect the generators' shares.
Before recent government hints that a subsidy may be given to coal
production, some energy specialists were pred-icting that PowerGen and
National Power would be able to provide about a 20 per cent dividend boost
from the improved earnings growth this year. While some still hold this
view, analysts are increasingly fearful that a subsidy on coal would not
only limit earnings, but also add weight to the regulatory environment -
with a Monopolies and Mergers Commission referral not ruled out - which in
turn could impinge on profits.
Yesterday the mood was more positive on the likely outcome; PowerGen
advanced 8 1/2 to 289p and National Power 8 to 289p. The regional companies
were also generally strong, with Manweb, ahead 13 at 506p, Norweb, up 12 at
489p, and Seeboard, 8 higher at 472p, among the main movers.
Enterprise weakens
The after-effects of a US listing by Enterprise Oil was said to be behind a
sharp fall in the UK share price yesterday. The independent exploration and
production company attempted to raise Dollars 150m (Pounds 98.6m) through an
initial public offering of American Depositary Shares in October.
A large chunk of the shares, however, were left with the underwriters, who
needed to offload them in the UK. Dealers said the stock was now overhanging
the market and responsible for the under-lying share price sliding 14 to
409p. Others suggested that the shares might merely have been consolidating
following a good run.
Courtaulds switch
Chemicals group Courtaulds tumbled 14 1/2 to 572 1/2 p after US investment
bank Lehman Brothers recommended switching out of the stock and into
Laporte, which rose 7 to 602p ex-rights.
Lehman analyst Mr Martin Glen argued that Laporte's price/earnings ratio was
some two points lower than Courtaulds' and it was more exposed to economic
recovery in North America. Also, Laporte was higher yielding and had greater
earnings growth potential. Laporte was supported by a number of other
houses, including Hoare Govett, which argues that the company's offer last
week for Evode (steady at 123p) was 'shrewd and well timed'.
Drug issues bought
Pharmaceuticals stocks held against the trend as one leading securities
house decided the tide was about to turn and became a strong buyer. The
sector was marginally up on the day and leading issues resisted selling
pressure.
Hoare Govett published an in-depth note entitled 'Calling the Bottom', which
argued that the sector presented a strong buying opportunity. Analyst Mr
Nigel Barnes said the sector could drift more in the short term but on a
12-month view it was 'extremely cheap'.
The house particularly likes SmithKline Beecham and said an R &amp; D
presentation in Philadelphia in March will highlight new products. It is
also buying Glaxo, Amersham International and London International.
SmithKline firmed 2 to 477p and 418p in the Units. Glaxo was a penny higher
at 724p, Amersham firm at 653p and LIG steady at 256p.
Dixons disappoints
The downward march in Dixons shares continued as the stores group revealed a
decline in its US fortunes far worse than the market's expectations. While
UK sales had held up well, particularly in the Christmas period, Dixons' US
electrical retailing chain Silo produced further losses and deepening gloom
among analysts. Dixons dropped 29 to 225p on exceptionally heavy turnover of
12m, the highest for around two years.
However, there were signs yesterday that the shares may soon find some
support. Mr Andy Hughes, stores specialist at Nomura, moved from a sell to a
buy, arguing that the fall had been overdone - the shares stood at 280p a
week ago - and that they now looked good value. 'Dixons is well placed for
recovery and the UK sales picture is very encouraging.' He added that the
revival in the US economy should come to the aid of Silo.
Bears of the stock forecast further falls. Mr Tony Shiret at BZW predicted
even worse losses in the US this year, despite Dixons' attempts to stem the
tide with a series of store closures. 'The shares are still too highly
rated,' he said.
There were other gloomy reports around the stores sector yesterday. The
well-signalled trading statement from Alexon proved this week's bear raiders
correct and the shares reacted accordingly, falling 8 to 68p. Warning of
flat earnings, the group said it did 'not anticipate recommending a final
dividend'.
Body Shop said UK sales in the pre-Christmas period were down 8 per cent.
The shares weakened 15 to 153p. Profits forecasts were pulled in to a range
of Pounds 19m to 22m, down about 10 per cent.
Rumours of downgradings in Great Universal Stores were heard. The shares
have fallen around a pound in the last week, including 37 yesterday to close
at 1613p. DIY worries and the continuing uncertainty over the strength of
the recovery knocked Kingfisher, off 18 at 554p. However, Next again
responded to talk that its sales remain firm, the shares adding 1 1/2 at
154p.
Oil shares were lower in the face of continued weakness in the oil price.
Spot and January Brent crude dipped below Dollars 17 per barrel, leading
some analysts to cut price forecasts for the year. BZW analyst Mr Jeremy
Elden cut his 1993 oil price forecast to Dollars 19.5 per barrel from
Dollars 21, but said investors should buy oil shares if Opec delivers
production cuts.
Shell Transport touched 524p but closed only a penny off at 529p, while
Lasmo dipped 4 to 146p. British Petroleum was steady at 237 1/2 p, although
Morgan Stanley was last night contacting clients to say it had cut
fourth-quarter earnings estimates. Analyst Mr Lars Reierson lowered his
forecast by Pounds 40m to Pounds 95m and said: 'US buying has been based on
over-optimistic earnings estimates. There will be little fundamental support
in the UK for the shares until the yield is a lot closer to Shell's'
Vodafone declined 9 to 399p on talk of regulatory interest in the cellular
market. Hoare Govett turned seller of the stock, citing aggressive
competition from Cellnet. Hoare also downgraded BT, the fully-paid losing 4
at 386p, and Cable and Wireless, 15 adrift at 692p, blaming UK recessionary
effects.
Firm results from First Leisure sent the shares forward 7 to 327p.
Championship prospects again lifted Manchester United, up 18 at 367p.
Bid speculation continued to circulate around Lucas Industries, driving the
shares forward 5 to 149p in trade of 3.2m. The Lucas warrants were also
actively traded. Volume jumped to 2.3m as they hardened 2 1/2 to 17 1/2 p.
Aero-engine manufacturer Rolls-Royce had a busy day. The shares fell 5 1/2
early in the session after Smith New Court cut dividend expectations for the
year to December 1992 by 2 1/2 p to 5p. Smith blamed the reduction on a lack
of pick-up in the spares business, technical factors, and the weak aircraft
market due to cancellations. Bargain hunters helped the stock recover to
close just 2 off at 106p on 6.3m traded.
Investors appreciated GKN's confirmation of plans for a new US plant and the
shares firmed 5 to 465p.
Public relations firm Shandwick performed well in percentage terms, rising 1
1/2 to 15 1/2 p ahead of results on January 26. Shandwick is well geared for
recovery in the US as it generates 50 per cent of profits there.
Talk of a Cazenove downgrade left Northern Foods 8 cheaper at 270p. James
Capel was said to be a buyer of Hillsdown, 8 higher at 143p.
