<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow shows resilience to Iraq
attack news
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US SHARE prices bounced back and forth yesterday before ending mostly firmer
in the wake of the attack by US and allied military forces on Iraq, writes
Patrick Harverson in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average was finally down just 1.08 at 3,263.56,
following a fall of more than 20 points earlier in the day. The more broadly
based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 finished 1.99 up at 433.03, while the American
SE composite ended 2.15 firmer at 398.56. The Nasdaq composite put in the
best performance, rising 7.33 to a record 686.78 on the back of a sharp rise
for Intel and strong demand for other technology stocks. Trading volume on
the New York SE was 245m shares.
Prices opened lower as investors continued to struggle to find good reasons
to buy stocks, while the absence of new economic statistics, and the lack of
movement from a becalmed bond market, ensured that trading remained
directionless.
The political backdrop deepened the gloom. Following rumours earlier in the
week of a planned attack on Iraq by US and allied forces, yesterday
afternoon the White House confirmed reports that a military strike had been
launched. The market took the news well, with share prices recovering almost
all the ground they lost earlier in the day.
Investors remained concerned, however, that a renewed conflict in the Gulf
could hinder economic recovery by depressing consumer and business
confidence, and possibly divert funds away from stocks to bonds.
Philip Morris receded Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 73 3/4 after disclosing that
shipments of its best-selling Marlboro cigarettes fell 5.6 per cent last
year - the steepest drop in the brand's history and much larger than the
industry-wide decline in sales.
A variety of factors undermined airline shares, including signs of another
price war, concern that conflict in the Middle East could push up fuel
prices and scare passengers away, and profit-taking following big gains
earlier in the week. UAL dropped Dollars 4 to Dollars 125 1/2 , Delta lost
Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 49 7/8 , USAir shed Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 13 7/8
and AMR, parent of American Airlines, slipped Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 67.
Defence stocks received a boost from the reports of an attack on Iraq.
General Dynamics roser Dollars 3 1/8 to Dollars 109 1/8 , Lockheed Dollars 1
to Dollars 56 1/4 and McDonnell Douglas Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 53 1/4 on
hopes that another war would boost government spending on weapons.
On the Nasdaq market, Intel soared Dollars 8 1/8 to Dollars 110 1/8 , an
all-time high, in volume of 10.7m shares after reporting that fourth-quarter
earnings rose to Dollars 1.97 a share, well above market estimates.
Canada
THE TORONTO market finished lower after continued heavy trading. The TSE 300
index was down 16.2 at 3,298.3 and declining issues led advances by 348 to
265 after volume of 45m shares valued at CDollars 414.8m.
Corby Distilleries reported significantly higher nine-month earnings. The
'A' stock appreciated CDollars  1/2 to CDollars 47.
