<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 93 / Foreign Exchanges: Dollar edges up on tensions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DOLLAR traded firmly against the D-Mark yesterday as Washington appeared
to be moving towards an attack on Iraq, but the US currency failed to break
through crucial technical barriers, writes James Blitz.
Political tensions in the world tend to be positive for the dollar, which is
deemed a 'safe haven' currency. Reports that President Bush was planning an
attack on Iraq pushed the dollar up to a high of DM1.6333 in European
trading, after a previous close of DM1.6320.
The US currency failed to make further headway. The market remains uncertain
whether President-elect Bill Clinton will announce a fiscal package to
stimulate the economy, because of indications that the US is already
enjoying a recovery.
Mr Neil MacKinnon of Citibank in London warned against buying the dollar as
a result of the Iraqi situation alone. He said the start of the Gulf war in
February 1991 was accompanied by a sharp fall in US consumer confidence, due
to rising oil and commodity prices. If repeated, this would depress the
currency again.
The dollar closed in London yesterday at DM1.6325. In New York, however, it
fell around 1 pfennig to end at DM1.6220.
The D-Mark continued to soften against the French franc as the Bundesbank
provided new indications that it might lower short-dated interest rates
again.
The Bundesbank added more liquidity to the German cash market in its weekly
inter-vention than had been expec-ted. Mr Helmut Schlesinger, the Bundesbank
president, improved sentiment by saying that the central bank was prepared
to show further flexibility on interest rates.
The franc rose to another six-week high against the German currency,
finishing in London at FFr3.391 to the D-Mark, after a previous close of
FFr3.395. It was some 4 centimes above its ERM floor against the D-Mark.
Given the more accommodating stance of the Bundesbank, there are growing
reasons to think the battle of the franc may have been truly won. But a
question hanging over the French currency is whether the Bundesbank will
ease monetary policy quickly enough to allow France to lower rates from
their high levels.
Mr MacKinnon said the Bundesbank will await the outcome of the talks on the
Solidarity Pact and the January inflation figures before making any more
decisions.
But Mr Christopher Potts of Banque Indosuez in Paris was quoted yesterday as
saying that another gesture on interest rates would probably be required
from the Bundesbank before the end of the month, if tensions were to be
allayed.
A devaluation of the Irish punt would also focus attention again on the
French currency. The Irish punt traded well above its ERM floors, but
one-month Irish punts were still quoted at around 30 per cent at the end of
the day.
</TEXT>
