<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 93 / World Commodities Prices: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOLD moved back towards a seven-year low on the London bullion market
yesterday. Despite news of President Bush's decision to launch a military
strike against Iraq, sentiment remains bearish. Comex gold futures were
lower at midday, with New York traders pointing out that the yellow metal
was continuing to lose its appeal as a safe haven during times of
international turmoil. 'The market is much more scared of central bank
selling and currency fluctuations than anything going on in the Middle
East,' said one. COPPER prices ended a nervous LME session higher, with the
market largely consolidating after Tuesday's massive declines, while
ALUMINIUM also finished steadier. Dealers said the copper market seemed to
pause amid confusion over its likely direction. Dips towards the Dollars
2,200 a tonne level for three-months delivery elicited buying support. In
Chicago WHEAT futures were sustaining early gains in late trading, under the
influence of the USDA's crop reports.
Compiled from Reuters
</TEXT>
