<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 93 / International Company News: International Paper slips into
the red after charge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL Paper, the US paper group which has been expanding fast in
Europe, reported a fourth-quarter net loss of Dollars 176m, after taking a
Dollars 263m after-tax charge for a productivity improvement programme.
The company said the results worked through at a loss of Dollars 1.46 a
share and were struck on sales of Dollars 3.4bn. Without the charges,
earnings totalled Dollars 87m, or 71 cents a share.
In the fourth quarter of 1991, the company earned Dollars 107m, or 96 cents
a share, before special charges and Dollars 66m, or 59 cents a share, after
charges.
Mr John Georges, chairman, said the company had achieved fourth-quarter
sales comparable to the second and third quarters, in spite of difficult
conditions in the US and European economies.
Pulp and paper sales rose to Dollars 995m, from Dollars 970m, while
paperboard and packaging improved to Dollars 895m from Dollars 870m and
distribution to Dollars 735m from Dollars 685m. Specialty products were up
to Dollars 545m from Dollars 485m, while timber and wood products were
unchanged at Dollars 350m.
For the full year, International Paper reported net earnings of Dollars 86m,
or 71 cents a share, after special charges and Dollars 405m, or Dollars 3.34
before charges.
Sales totalled Dollars 13.6bn, up from Dollars 12.7bn in 1991. Net earnings
in 1991 totalled Dollars 184m, or Dollars 1.66 after special charges and
Dollars 452m, or Dollars 4.09 before charges.
</TEXT>
