<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 93 / UK Company News: D Smith rises to Pounds 15m on back of
French unit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DAVID S SMITH, the paper and packaging group, announced pre-tax profits of
Pounds 15.2m for the half year ended October 31, against Pounds 3.1m
previously, which was struck after exceptional charges of Pounds 8.7m.
Mr Peter Williams, chief executive, said the contribution from Kaysersberg
Packaging, the French company acquired for Pounds 154m at the end of last
March, had more than offset the fall in profits in the UK paper division -
which only broke even.
UK packaging maintained profits, but the UK paper business had been hit by
unfair competition from Germany, Mr Williams said. The group has lodged a
complaint with the European Commission.
Group turnover rose from Pounds 171m to Pounds 259m, with Kaysersberg
chipping in Pounds 81.7m.
Operating profits of Pounds 19.6m (Pounds 11.4m), included Pounds 11.9m from
Kaysersberg, whose high margins offset a decline elsewhere. However, an
interest charge of Pounds 4.4m (Pounds 400,000 credit) was all due to
Kaysersberg.
In the UK, conditions were the worst he had experienced. But Mr Williams was
now more optimistic about a recovery in demand, with corrugated case
material volumes up 7 per cent, allowing a small price increase.
Redevelopment of the Kemsley mill was nearly complete and by the autumn it
would be producing at an annual rate of 400,000 tonnes. Kemsley has been
losing between Pounds 6m and Pounds 7m a year.
A labour dispute at the Abbey Corrugated sheet feeder plant cost more than
Pounds 1m and volumes there had yet to be rebuilt.
Mr John Miller, finance director, said that a high level of capital
spending, Pounds 27.7m in the first half (Pounds 7.4m) and an expected
Pounds 50m to Pounds 60m for the year (Pounds 21.7m), meant the group should
pay no tax in the current year and a low charge for the next couple of
years.
Net debt of Pounds 95.1m (cash of Pounds 13.7m) at the end of the half year
gave gearing of 43.9 per cent. However, fluctuations in the franc, in which
most of the debt is denominated, could change gearing significantly.
Earnings per share were 12.2p (3.4p after the exceptional charges) and the
interim dividend is unchanged at 2.75p.
COMMENT
Smith's share price initially rose in reaction to the figures, but after the
market considered the implications of a weaker continental market the shares
fell back to close 1p lower at 314p. Forecasts were shaded back too, an all
too familiar and depressing story with Smith. However, by comparison with
the substantial losses being made in other parts of the paper industry Smith
is doing well. There is still every hope of reasonable profits growth in
coming years. Forecasts of about Pounds 28m (Pounds 24.1m before
exceptionals) and no tax, give a prospective p/e of about 14, which gives
nothing away.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>David S Smith (Holdings).
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P265  Paperboard Containers and Boxes.
