<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 93 / Exchange group faces difficulty
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE contraction in the London insurance market could pose particular
problems for Market Building, the consortium of 24 insurance companies which
has spearheaded the development of an insurance exchange for companies, the
London Underwriting Centre.
Market Building (MBL) has a 25-year lease on custom-built premises at 3
Minster Court in the City, which it is hoping to sub-let to several dozen
London market companies. The project, conceived in the booming market of the
late 1980s, has been dogged with difficulty.
A fire in August 1991 devastated the building's interior forcing an
expensive refit and an 18-month delay in its opening.
The collapse of the property market has led many prospective tenants to
rethink their original commitments, while others have withdrawn from the
market or folded.
As a result, when the LUC opens in October, Mr David Trace, MBL company
secretary, expects the building to be only 70 per cent let, with consortium
members themselves occupying about half the space. Before the fire, the LUC
had let 94 per cent of the building's 300,000 sq ft of available space.
So far MBL has been unable to persuade the Institute of London Underwriters,
which provides an exchange and back-up facilities for just under 100 marine
and aviation companies, to move from its premises on Leadenhall Street to
Minster Court.
Worse still, LUC is now in direct competition with Lloyd's, which over the
past few months has begun to invite companies to share its headquarters with
the underwriting syndicates which already transact business there. Five
companies - Anglo American, AIG, QBE, Liberty Mutual and National Reliance -
are already operating there. Up to 30 other companies have shown interest.
In 1992 MBL reduced its rental charges twice in a move to retain interest
from sub-tenants. It will now cost tenants Pounds 40 per sq ft (including
service charges), a cut of about a third from the original asking price.
That is still higher than market rents of Pounds 22 per square foot
available for office space within a stone's throw of the Lloyd's market.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Market Building.
</CO>
