<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 93 / DTB and Matif in co-operation agreement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO OF Europe's largest futures exchanges, Germany's Deutsche Terminborse
and France's Matif, have agreed to link their markets, in the most
significant co-operation pact yet between exchanges.
Under the agreement, members of the DTB will be able to trade the Matif's
Ecu contracts, while Matif members will have access to the DTB's important
D-Mark interest rate contracts.
The link between the French and German market could help to draw business
away from the London International Financial Futures Exchange (Liffe), which
last year was Europe's most active futures market.
The agreement offers the DTB an opportunity to increase its market share in
German bund future trading, which is dominated by Liffe with around 70 per
cent of the market.
The Matif will also acquire the DTB's computerised trading system, which
will initially be used for trading its Ecu products.
Faced with increasing competition from over-the-counter products developed
by banks, futures exchanges have become increasingly keen to co-operate.
Technological advances have enabled traders around the world to come
together on screen-based systems, while the breakdown of barriers between
markets has spurred investor demand for a broader range of products.
Last year, four other European exchanges formed an alliance, First European
Exchanges (FEX), to extend the customer base for their contracts. Liffe is
continuing discussions with the Chicago Board of Trade to list some of each
others' products.
The Matif's decision to move products on to the DTB's computerised system
was influenced by the cost of trading less active contracts using the
traditional open-outcry method. New products may later be launched jointly,
or existing products added to the agreement.
The Matif said the link will have no impact on its agreement to join Globex,
the international after-hours trading system developed by the Chicago Board
of Trade, the Chicago Mercantile Exchange and Reuters. The DTB is still in
discussions with Globex. The Matif/DTB agreement is potentially open to
other exchanges, of which the Netherlands' European Options Exchange is
believed to be the most likely candidate.
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
