<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 93 / British soldier killed in Bosnia on convoy duty: UK to send
back-up forces to protect troops
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A BRITISH soldier was killed in Bosnia-Hercegovina yesterday, the first
British army fatality since troops joined the humanitarian aid effort in the
former Yugoslav republic.
The British government said UK forces would continue to supply humanitarian
aid for the victims of the civil war in Bosnia, backed by reinforcements
expected to be agreed by the British cabinet today.
The soldier was killed while accompanying a convoy along the route between
the Croatian coastal town of Split and Vitez in Bosnia.
The cabinet is due to agree on the dispatch of extra forces to back up the
UK's 2,400 troops in Bosnia, principally to increase protection for UK
soldiers.
Plans under discussion involve sending the aircraft carrier Ark Royal to the
Adriatic with Harrier jets and Sea King helicopters, as well as an artillery
battery to strengthen the capacity of British UN forces to respond to
attack.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, said Lance Corporal Wayne Edwards, 26,
'has lost his life in working to save the lives of many others'. Downing
Street said the risks of British involvement in Bosnia had never been
underestimated.
Officials said the twin-track strategy of helping victims of the civil war
while insisting that long-term peace in former Yugoslavia required a
negotiated settlement would continue. 'It is clear that we will carry on
providing humanitarian aid,' the prime minister's office said.
Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary, said British troops had saved many lives
in the region, besides escorting 147 convoys delivering a total of 12,000
tonnes of humanitarian aid.
European Community foreign ministers last night held an emergency meeting in
Paris to discuss Bosnia and the apparent breakthrough on Tuesday night at
the Geneva peace talks. They gave Bosnia's Serbs six days to accept
unconditionally the peace plan or face additional punitive measures by the
UN.
Mr Uffe Ellemann-Jensen, Danish foreign minister, said the EC would start
next week preparing plans to seal Serbia's borders, to set up a UN war
crimes tribunal, and to enforce no-fly zones over Bosnia. Mr Hans van den
Broek, EC external affairs commissioner, discussed with ministers the early
dispatch of observers to Serbia's neighbours, including Greece, to prepare
for stiffer sanctions.
Both men had earlier said the EC had to be ready to pursue the 'total
isolation' of Serbia if aggression against Bosnia continued. The Danish
foreign minister ruled out massive military intervention in former
Yugoslavia as 'not credible'.
Mr Radovan Karadzic, the Bosnian Serb leader, was last night due in
Belgrade, the Serbian capital. He will put the Geneva peace plan to his
parliament.
Macedonia row worsens, Page 2 German forces to UN, Page 2 Peace wins
reprieve, Page 19
