<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 93 / ICI may pay less for electricity to safeguard chlorine
business
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT plans to allow Imperial Chemical Industries to buy
electricity at cheaper rates than other UK industrial users in an attempt to
safeguard its chlorine business.
The move should secure 7,000 jobs at ICI's chlor-alkali plant at Runcorn,
Cheshire. PowerGen, the generating group, would be offered a licence to
supply electricity directly to the plant.
The proposals follow threats by ICI last year to abandon its chlorine
business unless it could secure supplies of cheap power. If ICI abandoned
chlorine production to foreign competition, it estimates the impact on the
UK balance of trade would be Pounds 1.5bn.
The group, which currently buys electricity from a spot market, experienced
sharply higher power costs following the industry's privatisation. ICI's
chlorine-based plants at Runcorn are the UK's largest consumers of
electricity - capable of using 250MW, equivalent to 1 per cent of the UK's
entire output.
The Department of Trade and Industry must now decide whether other large
industrial users should benefit from similar licences. Mr Peter Rost,
chairman of the Major Energy Users' Council, said he would want to assess
why ICI should be a special case, according to The Engineer, a specialist
magazine. Blue Circle Industries, the UK's largest cement manufacturer, and
British Steel are likely to want similar deals.
The DTI's proposals would allow PowerGen's Ince power-station near Runcorn
to supply the chlor-alkali plant directly. Ince is fuelled by oil or
Venezuelan bitumen. ICI would prefer to use the Fiddler's Ferry 2,000MW
plant five miles from Runcorn, which produces cheap electricity from coal.
The company has been paying up to Pounds 31 a megawatt hour for electricity
compared with under Pounds 20 before privatisation. Electricity now accounts
for about 70 per cent of the variable costs of ICI's chlorine production. In
November, ICI said it had given itself three months to sort out the problem.
</TEXT>
