<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 93 / Observer: Rescheduling
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Bob Phillis and Liz Forgan haven't even arrived at the BBC yet, but that has
not stopped their futures being mapped out. Phillis, the 47-year-old ITN
boss, who takes over as deputy director-general, is only one year younger
than John Birt, the new director-general. But he is already being seen as
Birt's natural successor.
The precedents are already well established. The last two deputy DGs, Birt
and Sir Michael Checkland, went on to get the top job. Liz Forgan, 48, who
comes from Channel 4 to be managing director of BBC Radio, would - after a
spell in BBC Television - be well placed to become the first woman to make
it to deputy DG.
Such changes may not be as far away as some appear to suspect. John Birt is
unlikely to stay longer than his five-year term.
Once the place is restructured and the BBC's Royal Charter is renewed in
1996, Big Brother Birt will want to be off in search of new conquests.
