<TEXT>
Sir, It was depressing to read that the City Corporation is once again
preparing to compromise London's diminishing built heritage, for a paltry
300,000 pieces of more than somewhat devalued silver ('Road in City to be
sold', January 12).
The last such occasion that professionally concerned me was the City
Corporation's sale to the London Docklands Development corporation of the
unique late 19th and early 20th century group of industrial buildings at St
George's Wharf, Deptford, which was then destroyed (in advance of possible
spot-listing) to make way for an unnecessarily elaborate feeder road and a
currently weed-encrusted 'development opportunity'.
Now Bucklersbury is likely to be similarly ripped up to make way for some
seedy 'arcade' (doubtless to be filled by unlettable retail premises)
running through what Prince Charles has rightly referred to as a 1930s
'wireless set', although, in the current climate, about the only way Lord
Palumbo will be able to fund its construction will be by emptying his own
pockets] We should expect a better standard of care for our heritage from
what is virtually the only efficient UK local authority. Brian H Gill,
261 Grove Street,
