<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Required watching tonight should be The Essential History of Europe; Greece
(BBC 2, 8.00). Greeks can generally be relied upon to lose all sense of
intellectual detachment whenever the subject arises of the relationship
between the modern Greek nation and the ancient Macedon of Philip and
Alexander. But as the matter of Macedon acquires ever more ominous
undertones, it is worth making the effort to disentagle the truth from
nationalistic myth-making.
The Sexual Imperative (C4, 9.00) is a highly watchable popularisation of the
neo-Darwinists' view of the mating game. Tonight's programme examines
polygamy versus monogamy in terms of the better stratagem for the survival
of genes into the next generation. When males of the species lock horns over
females there are winners and losers. Females, on the other hand, are
invariably the winners because they end up mating with the roughest,
toughest, genes on the block. Black Bag Special (C4, 8.30) follows up its
1991 story about the Cardiff Three by interviewing the men set free after
the latest revelation of a miscarriage of justice.
