<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Privacy may be protected by new law
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY and PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is examining civil law measures to defend privacy rights, to
add to the drafting of new criminal offences against the intrusive use of
electronic surveillance and telephoto lenses, it emerged yesterday.
A possible extension of the law of tort to cover privacy was raised by
senior ministers at a cabinet sub-committee after it was agreed to rush
forward publication of Sir David Calcutt QC's report on media behaviour to
today.
Alongside his central recommendation of a statutory press tribunal, Sir
David calls also for a new criminal offence of 'physical intrusion' to
prevent the use of bugging devices, long-range camera lenses and other
electronic equipment to illicitly gather information.
The new law would give the High Court the authority to issue injunctions
against the the publication of information gathered by such means. It would
also would provide for large damages to be awarded to the victims of such
intrusion.
Creating the separate breach-of-privacy tort, or civil wrong, would allow
individuals to sue for compensation in the courts when they believed they
could prove their private lives had been unreasonably invaded by intrusive
behaviour or reporting. It is recommended by Sir David.
There would be considerable legal complexities, however, over where the
mitigating defence of public interest applied and over how to cover legal
costs.
Downing Street said early publication of the controversial Calcutt report,
originally scheduled at the end of the month, was necessary to counter a
distorted debate of the subject misinformed by 'partial leakages' of its
findings.
The decision came as a new storm was mounting over claims that the security
services might be behind the leaking of tape-recordings of phone calls,
allegedly made by members of the royal family.
Lord Rees-Mogg, a former editor of The Times and now chairman of the
Broadcasting Standards Authority, made the charge yesterday after the
publication in Australia of an alleged conversation between the Prince of
Wales and his longtime friend, Mrs Camilla Parker Bowles.
A senior official rejected the claim as 'nonsensical' and dismissed any
possibility of an inquiry.
A formal response to the Calcutt report will be discussed at a full meeting
of the cabinet today. Ministers will also decide whether a statement should
be made to the Commons outlining the government's immediate reaction to its
findings.
Officials said it was quite possible that a statement would be made by Mr
Peter Brooke, the heritage secretary, but that a detailed government
response, including proposals on legislation, could be held back until
later.
</TEXT>
