<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Pessimism over recovery outlook
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ECONOMIC recovery in Britain will be constrained by rising current-account
and fiscal deficits and by fragile consumer confidence, according to a
report by the Commons Treasury and Civil Service committee, published
yesterday.
The report calls on the Bank of England to publish its advice to the
Treasury on monetary policy to reduce confusion in financial markets about
how policy is determined.
Giving a bleak view of the UK's medium-term prospects, the Tory-dominated
committee of backbench MPs says the scope for cuts in interest rates may be
limited by the need to 'avoid any further substantial depreciation of
sterling' to add to that which has already happened since Britain left the
European exchange rate mechanism last September.
The committee hints that substantial measures for growth may be needed in
the March Budget to produce a substantial upturn, but does not rule out the
need for tax rises to hold back the increase in the public-sector borrowing
requirement (PSBR).
According to the MPs, Britain faces 'an abyss of ever-increasing fiscal
deficits' over the next few years, assuming that growth remains fairly weak.
The latest City estimates put the likely PSBR in 1993-94 at about Pounds
50bn, after about Pounds 40bn this financial year.
The committee wants Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, to announce in the
Budget a strategy to bring down the deficit over the next few years,
possibly with a programme of gradually increased taxes and cuts in public
spending.
On the outlook for growth, the committee says: 'It is not clear whether the
limited policy measures announced during the Autumn Statement (published by
the Treasury in November) and reductions in interest rates will be
sufficient to counter the effects of rising unemployment and falling asset
prices on confidence.'
The MPs say a current-account deficit amounting to about 2 per cent of gross
domestic product in a recession suggests a 'structural' trouble arising out
of undue reliance on imports.
They warn: 'The UK may find itself suffering from an old-fashioned
balance-of-payments constraint with further downward pressure on sterling
requiring tighter policies which will in turn squeeze the personal sector's
disposable income.'
The MPs suggest the policy vacuum since Britain left the ERM - since when
the government has cut base rates by 3 percentage points to 7 per cent - has
left Mr Lamont with a 'pick and mix' approach to economic policy.
According to the committee, government statements since September on growth
strategies have 'led to some confusion as to what is now the main objective
of macroeconomic policy'.
It calls on Mr Lamont to reduce the confusion in the Budget by saying
exactly what economic indicators he is using to steer policy.
The report says a repeat of the fiasco surrounding the ERM last summer, when
Germany's desire to seek a general realignment of the system was not passed
on to Britain, might be avoided by better communications between member
states over realignment requests.
</TEXT>
