<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 93 / Political Notebook: Counting the cost of timidity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
What price radicalism? Whatever the precise figure, it is apparently still
too high for the leaders of Britain's two main political parties.
Beneath the intellectual torpor at Westminster, it is possible to detect a
shared assumption running from left to right that economic realities have
stripped the credibility from their central political ambitions.
Senior figures on both sides will acknowledge in a whisper that sooner or
later they will have to confront the structural tensions in the nation's
finances: the inexorable rise in a Pounds 75bn welfare budget and the tax
privileges for pensions and home ownership that cost the Treasury more than
Pounds 15bn a year.
Of itself, economic recovery will deliver neither the scope for income tax
cuts central to the Conservative philosophy nor the money for the industrial
strategy and the fairer society pledged by the Labour party.
As the Treasury and Civil Service committee reminded us yesterday, something
has to give.
If it does not, the present pessimistic projections for the budget deficit
may prove to err on the side of optimism.
That much should be common ground, even if for obvious reasons Mr John Major
must still proclaim publicly that most of the deficit will melt away with
the return of economic growth.
But even three or four years away from a general election neither Mr Major
nor Mr John Smith will engage in a serious debate about how the financial
circle can be squared.
Universal state pension and child benefit payments, tax exemption for
occupational pension schemes and mortgage interest tax relief are issues
still judged off-limits for public consideration by politicians.
For all the talk of the 'Clintonising' of the Labour party and of the
plethora of new ideas at Mr Major's brainstorming sessions at Chequers,
these are issues to be discussed at a distance.
Mr Smith has handed them over to an independent Commission on Social
Justice. In spite of its distance from official Labour policy, the party
leader has felt it necessary to make clear from the outset that the party
does not want to tamper with universal benefits.
On the Tory side, the debate is being left to the think tanks and to a
handful of Thatcherite true believers.
There are some members of the cabinet willing to discuss in private a
radical reduction in income tax reliefs or the eventual means-testing of
universal benefits.
The horrifying deficit forecasts being churned out by the Treasury's
computers have re-focused attention on mortgage interest relief and on the
present exemptions from value added tax.
But the prevailing mood in 10 Downing Street is risk- averse. The government
remains, in the words of one minister, distinctly 'wobbly'. Potentially
unpopular decisions are pushed to the bottom of Mr Major's in-tray.
So it has been left to the independent thinkers on the back benches at
Westminster to articulate the arguments.
The first - and most radical - salvo has been fired not by the Tory right
but by Mr Frank Field, the Labour MP for Birkenhead.
His central point is that Labour must turn on its head the traditional
preconception that an expanding welfare system is a measure of success.
Instead, the party should recognise it as an admission of failure.
Its concern should be with economic and social policies that pull people out
of the state safety net by spreading individual wealth as well as
employment.
Then comes the political ingenuity. Stealing some clothes from the Tory
right, Mr Field calls for what he terms the biggest-ever transfer of wealth
from corporate to individual hands: the unitisation of the Pounds 24bn in
occupational pension schemes to give every fund member ownership of their
share of the scheme.
The idea would be the logical conclusion of the shift to portable pensions
engineered by the Conservatives, marking the end of employer-controlled
final salary schemes.
That is only half the equation. Mr Field suggests that the huge transfer of
capital to individuals would provide the background for the phasing out of
the tax privileges of both pensions and mortgages.
The extra Pounds 15bn to Pounds 20bn in revenue could be used to allow
Labour to trump the Conservatives and pledge to slash the basic rate of
income tax by 10p to 15p in the pound. It would pave the way also for a cap
on the state pensions bill by allowing the targeting of future increases on
the poor.
It is an ambitious package. And Mr Field's conclusion that individual
ownership of pensions would nurture also a new culture of long-termism to
underpin Labour's industrial strategy may stretch credulity.
But Tory ministers are among those who admire its boldness. Mr Major and Mr
Smith should take note: the cost of timidity could well be higher than the
price of radicalism.
</TEXT>
<XX>
