<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Warning on lottery funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A LABOUR MP warned yesterday that the National Lottery may not be as
successful financially as ministers are assuming.
Mr Joe Ashton, MP for Bassetlaw, told Mr Peter Brooke, the national heritage
secretary, that the numbers 'just don't add up'.
Mr Ashton, speaking at a national heritage committee hearing, said that
suggestions of a Pounds 1.5bn turnover with prize money of about Pounds 14m
a week looked 'phenomenally optimistic.'
Apart from high start-up costs, it might be possible to equip only 10,000
retail outlets with the necessary computers in the first year. Smaller shops
and pubs would have to sell thousands of tickets to meet such a target.
Mr Brooke said the Pounds 1.5bn figure had been illustrative. If that turned
out to be the turnover, then prize money of Pounds 14m a week would be
possible, because the payouts of many lotteries around the world varied from
48 per cent to 52 per cent of revenue, he said.
A number of MPs also expressed concern yesterday at the effect the lottery
might have on the football pools and in particular their requests for 'a
level playing field'.
Although he repeated previous statements that the government would keep an
open mind as the National Lottery bill went through parliament, Mr Brooke
did not appear to hold out much hope on the main changes the pools companies
are asking for.
Mr Brooke said that if the government started adjusting, that might damage
the lottery's chances of success. If pools companies were allowed to
advertise on television the government 'would receive pressure that all
gambling should be allowed to advertise.
</TEXT>
