<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Cross-party backing for action
against Iraq
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AS THE western allies began a limited air strike against Iraq, the
government last night secured effective cross-party support for military
action, provided that the measures were in compliance with international
law.
Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary, told MPs that Iraq had 'not complied
with the representations made to them on the southern no-fly zone, they have
violated the border with Kuwait, they have moved missiles into northern
Iraq'.
He promised that measures taken 'would need to be and would be in full
compliance with the international law.'
Britain hoped that the Iraqi regime 'will not miscalculate, that the
violations of the border will cease immediately . . . and that Iraq will
comply with the United Nations,' Mr Douglas Hogg, foreign office minister,
later added.
For Labour, Mr George Robertson, foreign affairs spokesman, said there was
widespread international agreement that Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein's recent
conduct had been 'designed as deliberate and calculated provocation by a
despicable regime'.
Emphasising there was 'no question at all' that Saddam must comply with the
provisions of UN resolutions, he said Labour would continue to support the
air exclusion zones and their enforcement. He welcomed the government's
assurance that action would be in accordance with international law.
Two Labour MPs - Mr Tam Dalyell and Mr George Galloway - formally exempted
themselves from the frontbench consensus on last night's action. Mr Dalyell
said that Egypt and Bahrain 'do not support us in military action in these
circumstances.'
Sir David Steel, for the Liberal Democrats, said it was important that the
government enjoyed cross-party support for 'whatever action they take in an
international context against Saddam Hussein'.
Mr Gerald Kaufman, former shadow foreign secretary, said many MPs would
support action to ensure Iraq obeyed ceasefire resolutions - 'provided
civilians are protected'.
Mr Jack Cunningham, shadow foreign secretary, meanwhile, pressed Mr Hurd
regarding newspaper reports that he had 'personally authorised a visit to
Britain from people from Iraq to discuss the purchase with GEC of
telecommunications systems'.
Mr Hurd said it was certain that neither he nor a colleague would authorise
action 'which could have led anyone . . . to believe it was correct or
possible under our law to break the sanctions of the UN'.
</TEXT>
