<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Confidence in business declines in
Scotland
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUSINESS confidence in Scotland declined slightly in the last quarter of
1992 and demand contracted in almost all sectors, according to the latest
quarterly survey of Scottish business opinion, James Buxton writes.
The survey, by Scotland's chambers of commerce and analysed by the Fraser of
Allander Institute, Scotland's principal economic research organisation,
said business confidence fell in manufacturing, distribution and tourism.
There was a slight increase in confidence in construction, but from a low
base.
The only sector to report buoyant and rising demand was manufactured
exports.
Expectations for the first quarter of 1993 are for a continuation of
recessionary conditions but with a slower rate of contraction than in the
last quarter of 1992.
