<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 93 / Most unionists 'in white-collar jobs'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOST trade unionists are now non-manual workers and have educational
qualifications of A level or equivalent, while 23 per cent have a university
degree or equivalent.
The 1991 Labour Force Survey, published today in the Department of
Employment's Employment Gazette, estimates that 53 per cent of union members
have full-time white-collar jobs and only 24 per cent work in manufacturing.
The figures reflect the higher levels of unionisation in the public sector
among health, teaching and central and local-government professionals.
Union density among those at work has fallen to 33 per cent but the gender
gap is narrowing. In 1991 42 per cent of men at work belonged to a union
compared with 32 per cent of women. In 1948 fewer than 20 per cent of trade
unionists were women. That proportion has risen to 40 per cent.
Unions continue to find it hard to recruit part-time workers - only 22 per
cent belong to a union - but 23 per cent of part-time women workers were in
unions, compared with 12 per cent of men. The study also shows that workers
under 24 are less likely to be in unions than other age groups. Thirty-seven
per cent of workers, including the unemployed and self-employed, were trade
unionists in 1991, the fewest since the middle of the Second World War and
15 percentage points less than in 1978, when membership peaked.
Northern England has the highest union density, with 46 per cent of the
workforce unionised. The lowest is in East Anglia, with 25 per cent. While
33 per cent of white workers were in unions, 46 per cent of West
Indian/Guyanese, 33 per cent of Indians and 27 per cent of
Pakistani/Bangladeshi workers were unionised. Employment Gazette. HMSO.
Pounds 4.70.
</TEXT>
