<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 93 / Under 21s slip behind in pay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FIRST detailed survey of the effect of removing young people from the
protection of wages councils, which set minimum pay rates for about 2.5m
workers, has found that their pay fell relative to older workers in two out
of three sectors.
People under 21 years were removed from the Wages Councils in a reform of
the system in 1986. The Employment Bill going through its committee stage in
the Commons seeks to abolish the wages councils completely.
Department of Employment research on the effects of removing
under-21-year-olds concluded that there was no evidence of systematic falls
in the pay of young people relative to the pay of employees aged 21 years
and over.
In the hotel and catering sector, however, the pay of young male workers
fell 4.6 per cent between 1986 and 1992 and the pay of young female workers
fell 9.7 per cent when compared with workers over 21.
In retailing, the pay of young male workers fell 1.1 per during the period
while that of young female workers fell 2.2 per relative to pay for older
workers.
The pay of young male sales assistants rose 4.3 percentage points more than
for older workers and that for young female hairdressers rose 2.8 per cent
more than for older workers.
</TEXT>
