<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 93 / Attack on Iraq: US warns of more raids if Iraq transgresses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM and DAVID WHITE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, HIGH WYCOMBE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LAST NIGHT'S air raids against Iraq targeted only missile batteries and
associated infrastructure. But, said the White House, Mr Marlin Fitzwater,
the US stood ready to take 'additional forceful actions' with its allies if
Iraq continued to flout 'the will of the international community.'
Some officials within the Bush administration had advocated a more violent
response, possibly extending to the annihilation of an entire army division.
Yesterday's operation was 'a spanking, not a full beating' they said.
A US general last night expressed cautious optimism about the results of the
raid.
General Joseph Hoar, commander in chief of US Central Command, which
supervises the Middle East region, said the attack, involving 80 strike
aircraft and 30 support planes, had targeted either mobile surface to air
missile batteries or stationary air defence facilities in the regions of
Telil, Samawah, Najaf and al-Amarah.
He said the aircraft had taken off from a number of sites in the Arabian
peninsula, as well as from the aircraft carrier Kitty Hawk, but declined to
say which other countries, besides the US, UK and France, had participated
in the raid.
Coalition planes had encountered a small amount of anti-aircraft artillery
fire, but no missiles, he said, adding that it would take several hours to
analyse film and assess the results of the raid.
At the RAF Command Centre in High Wycombe, Air Chief Marshal Sir John
Thomson, chief of RAF Strike Command, said the operation appeared to have
been 'commendably successful'.
It was very similar to many undertaken in the 1991 Gulf campaign although on
a relatively limited scale. The attacks had been calculated to create a
minimum chance of 'collateral damage' - meaning civilian casualties.
Four RAF Tornado GR1 bombers took part in the attack on the al-Amarah base
just south of the 32nd parallel. They dropped six 1,000lb laser-guided bombs
from medium level on two parts of the site. All the crews returned safely.
US administration officials over the last few days have been at pains to
portray Iraq's actions as forming a pattern of provocation: attacks on
United Nations relief operations; flights in the no-fly zone in southern
Iraq; threatening missile movements; unauthorised incursions across the
Kuwaiti border; and impermissible restrictions on UN weapons inspectors.
The air strikes however, made it clear that there are two types of
provocation: those which threaten allied pilots, and those which do not. Mr
Fitzwater said yesterday that the raid came in response to Iraq's failure to
comply with the 48-hour ultimatum issued on January 6 by the three allies,
in conjunction with Russia, demanding the withdrawal of missiles from the
southern no-fly zone.
Although US officials claimed over the weekend that Iraq had, indeed,
removed these anti-aircraft missiles, that ultimatum was subsequently
breached. 'The coalition is acting to restore an environment which poses no
threat to coalition aircraft,' Mr Fitzwater said.
Mr Fitzwater mentioned only in passing Iraq's repeated flouting of Monday's
Security Council warning against incursions into Kuwait; indeed, he made it
clear that President George Bush's decision to bomb Iraq had been taken on
Monday, before the Security Council issued its statement.
However, the dispatch of a battalion-strength US task force to Kuwait may
provide some more forceful backing to the unarmed UN observer mission
manning the Iraq-Kuwait border.
General Hoar said, however, that the battalion, from the 1st Cavalry
Division at Fort Worth, Texas, would not enter the demilitarised zone along
the border, but would conduct exercises with Kuwaiti forces in an area
northwest of Kuwait City.
</TEXT>
